.TH SIMPLE_SHELL 1 "April 2026" "Holberton School" "User Commands"

.SH NAME
simple_shell - a minimal Unix command interpreter

.SH SYNOPSIS
.B ./shell

.SH DESCRIPTION
.B simple_shell
is a basic Unix-like command interpreter written in C.
It reads user input from standard input, parses the input into tokens,
and executes commands either as built-in functions or external programs.

The shell runs in an interactive loop, displaying a prompt when
connected to a terminal.

.SH FEATURES
.IP \(bu 4
Custom command tokenization with support for quoted strings
.IP \(bu
Execution of external programs using fork and execve
.IP \(bu
PATH resolution using a custom environment lookup
.IP \(bu
Built-in commands: exit and env
.IP \(bu
Dynamic memory management for command parsing

.SH COMMAND PARSING
Input is split into tokens using a custom tokenizer.

The tokenizer:
.IP \(bu 4
Uses space, tab, and newline as delimiters
.IP \(bu
Treats text inside single (' ') or double (" ") quotes as a single token
.IP \(bu
Modifies the input string in-place

Example:
.nf
Input:  echo "hello world"
Tokens: ["echo", "hello world"]
.fi

.SH BUILTIN COMMANDS
.TP
.B exit
Terminates the shell.

.TP
.B env
Prints all environment variables to standard output.

.SH COMMAND EXECUTION
For each command entered, the shell:
.IP 1. 4
Displays a prompt if running interactively
.IP 2.
Reads a line using getline
.IP 3.
Splits the line into an argument array
.IP 4.
Checks for built-in commands
.IP 5.
Searches for the executable in PATH if needed
.IP 6.
Creates a child process using fork
.IP 7.
Executes the command using execve
.IP 8.
Waits for the child process to terminate

If the command is not found, execution fails.

.SH PATH RESOLUTION
The shell searches for executables using the PATH environment variable.

PATH is retrieved using a custom implementation of getenv.

Each directory is checked by constructing a full path and verifying it
using stat().

If a match is found, the command may be replaced with its full path.

.SH ENVIRONMENT
Environment variables are accessed using a custom function.

.TP
.B PATH
Used to locate executable files.

.SH MEMORY MANAGEMENT
The shell dynamically allocates memory for:
.IP \(bu 4
Token arrays
.IP \(bu
Duplicated strings
.IP \(bu
Constructed file paths

Allocated memory is freed after use to prevent leaks.

.SH RETURN VALUE
The shell runs until:
.IP \(bu 4
The user enters the exit command
.IP \(bu
End-of-file (Ctrl+D) is encountered

.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
Start the shell:
.B ./shell

.TP
Example session:
.nf
$ ./shell
shell$ ls -l
shell$ echo "Hello world"
shell$ env
shell$ exit
.fi

.SH LIMITATIONS
.IP \(bu 4
No support for pipes (|)
.IP \(bu
No support for input/output redirection (<, >)
.IP \(bu
No command chaining (;)
.IP \(bu
No signal handling (e.g., Ctrl+C behavior not customized)
.IP \(bu
Limited error reporting

